text:
there are two different number systems in Japanese, one of them is native and the other is of Chinese origin.
the native numbers are: hito, futa, mi, yo, itsu, mu, nana, ya, kokono and tou.
the derived numbers are the ones everyone's heard of by now, the usual ichi, ni, san from middle Chinese *'yit, *nuiyh, *sam.
the Japanese borrowed these numbers a very long time ago, so the old ones they used fell out of regular use however was still kept around for things like counting items in the market. those numbers used to sound like: pit√∂, puta, mi, y√∂, itu, mu, nana, ya, k√∂k√∂n√∂ and tou.
